docs.abstract: Video footage of the fatal encounter included critical moments in which police officers kicked, punched and pepper-sprayed Mr. Nichols, 29, while he screamed.
docs.snippet: Video footage of the fatal encounter included critical moments in which police officers kicked, punched and pepper-sprayed Mr. Nichols, 29, while he screamed.
docs.lead_paragraph: MEMPHIS — The police officers kicked Tyre Nichols in the head, pepper-sprayed him and hit him repeatedly with a baton, even as he showed no signs of fighting back. At one point, after Mr. Nichols stood up, one officer struck him with at least five forceful blows while another held Mr. Nichols’s hands behind his back.

headline.main: Tyre Nichols Cried in Anguish. Memphis Officers Kept Hitting.
headline.print_headline: Held and Beaten by Memphis Police as He Cried, ‘Mom’

docs.abstract: They shatter the trust of the community, and the results can be deadly.
docs.snippet: They shatter the trust of the community, and the results can be deadly.
docs.lead_paragraph: The website of the Memphis Police Department includes an entire section called “Reimagine Policing.” The introduction emphasizes that trust is the key to effective law enforcement and proclaims the department’s participation in reform efforts such as President Barack Obama’s 21st Century Policing program, de-escalation training and the “8 Can’t Wait” reforms proposed by the group Campaign Zero.

headline.main: Tyre Nichols’s Death Proves Yet Again That ‘Elite’ Police Units Are a Disaster

docs.abstract: Sometimes body camera footage is made public within hours; other times it takes months. Memphis officials chose a time when businesses would be closed and the charges over Tyre Nichols’s death were already known.
docs.snippet: Sometimes body camera footage is made public within hours; other times it takes months. Memphis officials chose a time when businesses would be closed and the charges over Tyre Nichols’s death were already known.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bracing for public outrage, the authorities in Memphis have chosen to wait until shortly after 6 p.m. Central time on Friday to release video of the police encounter that resulted in Tyre Nichols’s death.

headline.main: Release of police video is timed with public reaction in mind.

docs.lead_paragraph: Diversity training has been around for decades, long before the country’s latest round of racial reckoning. But after George Floyd’s murder — as companies faced pressure to demonstrate a commitment to racial justice — interest in the diversity, equity and inclusion (D.E.I.) industry exploded. The American market reached an estimated $3.4 billion in 2020.

headline.main: What if Diversity Training Is Doing More Harm Than Good?
headline.print_headline: What if Diversity Trainings Do More Harm Than Good?

docs.lead_paragraph: On a day in June 2020, Alice Jones was in her Brooklyn apartment getting ready to attend a Black Lives Matter rally. Dr. Jones, a flutist and composer who serves as an assistant dean and faculty member at the Juilliard School, was adamant about expressing herself as a Black classical musician.

headline.main: A Black Composer’s Legacy Flourishes 500 Years After His Birth

docs.lead_paragraph: Before Tyre Nichols moved to Memphis — before he was brutally beaten on a Saturday night by police officers there — he lived in California, in the Sacramento area, where he hung out with a crowd of skateboarders.

headline.main: From Sacramento to Memphis, Tyre Nichols Cut His Own Path
headline.print_headline: A ‘Chill’ Man Trying to Cut His Path

docs.abstract: Mr. Nichols’s family and activists had demanded the scuttling of the group, the Scorpion unit, which patrolled high-crime areas of the city.
docs.snippet: Mr. Nichols’s family and activists had demanded the scuttling of the group, the Scorpion unit, which patrolled high-crime areas of the city.
docs.lead_paragraph: MEMPHIS — The Memphis Police Department said on Saturday that it had disbanded a specialized group known as the Scorpion unit after five of its officers were charged with second-degree murder in the death of Tyre Nichols, a 29-year-old Black man who was shown on video being kicked, struck and pepper-sprayed by those officers.

headline.main: Memphis Police Disband Unit Whose Officers Were Charged in Tyre Nichols’s Death
headline.print_headline: Memphis Police Disband Special Unit After Death

headline.main: Special Memphis Police Unit Was Supposed to Stop Violence

docs.abstract: “This person was not treated as a human being,” one expert said.
docs.snippet: “This person was not treated as a human being,” one expert said.
docs.lead_paragraph: Experts in police training who reviewed videos released on Friday of the fatal beating of Tyre Nichols in Memphis said they believed there was no justification for the actions of the police officers involved, who have been charged with crimes including second-degree murder in his death.

headline.main: ‘The definition of excessive force’: Policing experts assess the beating of Tyre Nichols.
